WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.100 --> 00:00:00.500
All right.

2
00:00:03.720 --> 00:00:07.660
All right, while people are coming in, this QR code is for

3
00:00:07.840 --> 00:00:11.360
if you would like to type your question. We have microphones.

4
00:00:11.420 --> 00:00:14.920
You are definitely welcome to ask your question in person, but if you would rather

5
00:00:14.960 --> 00:00:15.560
type it in,

6
00:00:16.820 --> 00:00:20.240
you can do that online and it will pop onto the computer here, and we'll read it

7
00:00:20.320 --> 00:00:20.540
out.

8
00:00:24.400 --> 00:00:24.740
Okay.

9
00:00:30.120 --> 00:00:30.660
All right.

10
00:00:34.800 --> 00:00:36.260
All right. With that, we'll get started.

11
00:00:36.340 --> 00:00:39.500
We have a great session today on non-clinical models of cancer.

12
00:00:41.880 --> 00:00:45.600
And I just wanted to introduce the problem that we're trying to

13
00:00:45.700 --> 00:00:49.520
solve, which really is that we have great

14
00:00:50.560 --> 00:00:54.220
high impact studies looking in very mechanistic detail in mice,

15
00:00:54.660 --> 00:00:56.740
sometimes with impressive survival curves.

16
00:00:57.220 --> 00:01:00.410
And so how do we take these findings and translate them into

17
00:01:00.460 --> 00:01:03.940
humans in a way that leads to successful clinical trials?

18
00:01:04.390 --> 00:01:08.100
And so some of the initial questions that come out of this, does my target

19
00:01:08.140 --> 00:01:12.060
pathway even exist in humans? While we can certainly ask, okay,

20
00:01:12.140 --> 00:01:14.600
is my gene of interest there, or my protein?

21
00:01:14.660 --> 00:01:17.560
We have lots of atlas data from many human

22
00:01:17.600 --> 00:01:21.580
tissues. It doesn't necessarily tell you that

23
00:01:21.600 --> 00:01:25.440
that entire pathway and all the proteins that interact with your target gene are

24
00:01:25.460 --> 00:01:28.860
there. So does your drug act similarly in

25
00:01:28.920 --> 00:01:31.140
humans? Certainly an open question.

26
00:01:31.180 --> 00:01:34.090
Are there additional redundancies or regulatory pathways?

27
00:01:34.590 --> 00:01:36.880
Toxicities are incredibly difficult to address.

28
00:01:36.940 --> 00:01:37.200
And then,

29
00:01:38.340 --> 00:01:42.310
is this mouse model that you've used actually relevant to most patients with the

30
00:01:42.380 --> 00:01:45.880
disease, or is it just some subset, and how can we better get at these

31
00:01:45.920 --> 00:01:46.440
questions?

32
00:01:47.480 --> 00:01:51.160
So I think our session today really has sort of three main focuses.

33
00:01:51.400 --> 00:01:53.740
One is improving our mouse models.

34
00:01:54.680 --> 00:01:58.650
Conventionally, we knock out some gene and then implant those knockout

35
00:01:58.760 --> 00:02:02.200
tumors into the flanks of mice. This is very simple to

36
00:02:02.240 --> 00:02:06.050
do, but we're going to hear from three speakers about using,

37
00:02:06.080 --> 00:02:09.769
rather than just whole knockout, point mutations identified from

38
00:02:09.840 --> 00:02:13.740
actual human cancers, and really exquisite

39
00:02:14.000 --> 00:02:17.700
techniques to implant tumors orthotopically in that

40
00:02:17.740 --> 00:02:21.430
relevant organ site. We've got brain, bladder, and

41
00:02:21.660 --> 00:02:25.580
mammary gland all represented. So three outstanding

42
00:02:25.700 --> 00:02:26.080
talks,

43
00:02:26.920 --> 00:02:29.580
looking at familial glioma variants.

44
00:02:29.840 --> 00:02:33.800
Then we'll hear on aging and breast cancer oncogenesis.

45
00:02:34.880 --> 00:02:37.880
Next on fibroblast crosstalk in bladder cancer.

46
00:02:39.820 --> 00:02:43.540
Another issue is that maybe the problems or challenges we face in

47
00:02:43.580 --> 00:02:46.540
humans are more complex than looking in young mice.

48
00:02:46.620 --> 00:02:50.480
And so following on the aging theme, clonal hematopoiesis is

49
00:02:51.080 --> 00:02:53.940
common in humans as we age,

50
00:02:54.820 --> 00:02:58.000
such that the patient population overlapping with many

51
00:02:58.060 --> 00:03:00.620
cancers, often has clonal hematopoiesis.

52
00:03:00.660 --> 00:03:03.060
How does this interface, and how do we model that?

53
00:03:03.140 --> 00:03:06.760
So we're going to hear about nanobioreactors using human

54
00:03:06.780 --> 00:03:08.060
hematopoietic stem cells.

55
00:03:09.160 --> 00:03:13.000
And then we'll close our session really thinking about how we use the human

56
00:03:13.140 --> 00:03:17.109
tumor to model human cancers. And so we hear a lot about

57
00:03:17.160 --> 00:03:20.920
organoids, but we've got three examples of organotypic cultures

58
00:03:20.960 --> 00:03:24.740
where we isolate the human tumor, either by biopsy or

59
00:03:24.820 --> 00:03:28.660
surgical resection. And then it comes with not only the tumor cells, but

60
00:03:28.720 --> 00:03:31.340
also all of the fibroblasts and immune cells that are in there.

61
00:03:31.800 --> 00:03:35.740
And so can we use this for drug screening and analyzing by flow,

62
00:03:35.840 --> 00:03:39.740
by cytokine profiling, or by tumor viability to ask how does

63
00:03:39.750 --> 00:03:43.180
that tumor microenvironment respond to drugs?

64
00:03:43.240 --> 00:03:47.220
So three great talks on this. We'll hear on modeling in

65
00:03:47.240 --> 00:03:48.549
non-small cell lung cancer,

66
00:03:49.720 --> 00:03:53.540
testing antibody drug conjugates in some of these platforms, and then we'll

67
00:03:53.580 --> 00:03:57.340
conclude with cytokine profiling from these ex vivo cultures, and does that

68
00:03:57.400 --> 00:03:59.080
actually predict patient outcome?

69
00:04:00.300 --> 00:04:03.680
So with that, I'm very excited to introduce our first

70
00:04:04.420 --> 00:04:07.940
speaker, who is Tiffany Choi, who's a graduate

71
00:04:08.080 --> 00:04:08.540
student

72
00:04:09.520 --> 00:04:10.600
from Baylor College.

73
00:04:11.800 --> 00:04:12.600
This should come up.

74
00:04:13.780 --> 00:04:17.620
Tiffany? Oh, start. There we go. All

75
00:04:17.661 --> 00:04:18.340
right. Welcome.

76
00:04:28.320 --> 00:04:30.320
All right. So hi everyone. My name is Tiffany.

77
00:04:30.340 --> 00:04:33.900
I'm a graduate student at Baylor College of Medicine, and today I'll discuss

78
00:04:34.300 --> 00:04:36.220
part of my thesis project, which involves

79
00:04:37.120 --> 00:04:39.740
the role of a germline variant in familial glioma.

80
00:04:40.940 --> 00:04:44.740
So as a bit of a background, over 200,000 new cases of

81
00:04:44.780 --> 00:04:47.920
gliomas are diagnosed each year, and the World Health

82
00:04:48.000 --> 00:04:51.780
Organization defines these as either malignant or non-malignant,

83
00:04:52.040 --> 00:04:55.760
malignant tumors accounting for about a quarter of these

84
00:04:55.800 --> 00:04:58.990
cases. And of the malignant gliomas,

85
00:04:59.420 --> 00:05:01.420
glioblastoma, which is the most devastating

86
00:05:02.380 --> 00:05:05.740
and untreatable cancer, makes up about half of them.

87
00:05:06.860 --> 00:05:10.520
So the current standard of care right now is maximal surgical resection, along with

88
00:05:10.560 --> 00:05:14.460
radiation and chemotherapy. However, despite these current treatment regimens,

89
00:05:15.560 --> 00:05:17.820
the survival is still relatively poor.

90
00:05:18.520 --> 00:05:20.620
So as you can see here, compared to

91
00:05:21.680 --> 00:05:25.360
patients with other CNS tumors, glioblastoma patients see a five-year relative

92
00:05:25.440 --> 00:05:29.160
survival rate of merely 7%. Now, this hasn't really changed over the

93
00:05:29.220 --> 00:05:33.000
many decades, so this really highlights the critical need for

94
00:05:33.020 --> 00:05:34.500
efficacious new therapies.

95
00:05:35.460 --> 00:05:37.320
So how do we go about approaching this?

96
00:05:38.800 --> 00:05:42.660
So, most gliomas actually arise from sporadic

97
00:05:42.720 --> 00:05:43.380
mutations,

98
00:05:44.400 --> 00:05:48.100
and WHO has really incorporated this to categorize and

99
00:05:48.160 --> 00:05:49.520
diagnose patients better.

100
00:05:50.500 --> 00:05:54.120
However, we can't really use these as predictive markers since they do occur at

101
00:05:54.160 --> 00:05:54.560
random.

102
00:05:55.600 --> 00:05:59.340
So alternatively, we can look at the 5 to 10% of gliomas that

103
00:05:59.380 --> 00:06:02.000
occur with hereditary predisposition.

104
00:06:02.060 --> 00:06:04.210
So these are familial glioma cases,

105
00:06:05.260 --> 00:06:08.960
and they're roughly defined as having one or more family member that has been

106
00:06:09.000 --> 00:06:12.124
diagnosed with a brain tumor.And although these

107
00:06:12.884 --> 00:06:16.804
familial glioma cases account for only a small portion of all gliomas,

108
00:06:17.624 --> 00:06:21.614
the field has really been able to study these cases and

109
00:06:21.684 --> 00:06:24.644
define a few glioma predisposition genes.

110
00:06:25.444 --> 00:06:29.204
And obviously, the list is really short, but the goal really is

111
00:06:29.264 --> 00:06:33.104
to leverage what we know about these familial glioma cases in

112
00:06:33.164 --> 00:06:33.904
order to

113
00:06:34.904 --> 00:06:38.864
identify and characterize novel germline variants that

114
00:06:38.904 --> 00:06:41.084
could predispose one to developing glioma.

115
00:06:42.704 --> 00:06:46.504
So we started with looking at a gene that we study in the lab, DAM2.

116
00:06:47.164 --> 00:06:50.844
And when we look at the human TCGA

117
00:06:50.924 --> 00:06:54.914
database, we can see that the DAM2 mRNA expression is enriched in

118
00:06:54.944 --> 00:06:58.304
high-grade glioma as well as low-grade glioma.

119
00:06:58.524 --> 00:07:01.924
And not shown here, my lab has also determined that the

120
00:07:01.984 --> 00:07:05.944
overexpression of wild-type DAM2 does promote tumorigenesis in in

121
00:07:05.984 --> 00:07:08.024
vitro and in vivo glioma mouse models.

122
00:07:08.544 --> 00:07:11.844
So with that information, we wanted to know if there exists any

123
00:07:11.884 --> 00:07:15.504
pathological variants of DAM2 in familial glioma

124
00:07:15.514 --> 00:07:19.074
patients. So with the help of Dr. Melissa Bondy at Stanford,

125
00:07:19.864 --> 00:07:23.644
she helped us identify five DAM2 germline variants

126
00:07:24.444 --> 00:07:28.164
in familial glioma patients, and

127
00:07:29.224 --> 00:07:32.984
four of the variants occur in patients with IDH wild-type or

128
00:07:33.044 --> 00:07:36.524
high-grade gliomas, and one patient is afflicted with

129
00:07:36.584 --> 00:07:39.344
oligodendroglioma, which is a type of low-grade glioma.

130
00:07:40.344 --> 00:07:43.584
So with these variants identified, we wanted to then know if they had any

131
00:07:43.624 --> 00:07:45.864
functional role in glioma development.

132
00:07:47.044 --> 00:07:50.384
So in order to do that, I overexpressed each of these variants in a

133
00:07:50.464 --> 00:07:52.954
patient-derived GBM stem-like cell.

134
00:07:53.624 --> 00:07:57.204
And you can see here that the cells that overexpress the R404W

135
00:07:57.224 --> 00:08:01.124
variant actually produces the largest tumor sphere size compared to all

136
00:08:01.164 --> 00:08:05.144
the other groups. And I was curious to see whether this would be recapitulated

137
00:08:05.204 --> 00:08:08.664
in vivo, so I did a classic orthotopic

138
00:08:08.704 --> 00:08:12.564
xenograft with these variant overexpressing cells, and we see

139
00:08:12.604 --> 00:08:16.264
similar results in that the R404W overexpressing

140
00:08:16.304 --> 00:08:20.064
cells have a greater tumor size compared to the DAM2 wild-type

141
00:08:20.204 --> 00:08:22.224
control as well as the GFP control.

142
00:08:22.544 --> 00:08:25.904
You can see this by bioluminescence imaging as well as

143
00:08:25.984 --> 00:08:29.904
cross-sectional histology analysis for gross tumor volume as well

144
00:08:29.984 --> 00:08:32.845
as proliferation by Ki-67 expression.

145
00:08:33.845 --> 00:08:37.824
So in total or together, the in vitro and in vivo data suggest

146
00:08:37.884 --> 00:08:41.524
that the DAM2 R404W variant can promote tumor growth.

147
00:08:42.184 --> 00:08:45.704
However, these experiments were done in models that may not fully

148
00:08:45.724 --> 00:08:49.164
recapitulate what we might see in human patients, as the

149
00:08:49.224 --> 00:08:53.024
overexpression here is limited to just the tumor cells, and these

150
00:08:53.184 --> 00:08:56.424
mice are also immunodeficient, so lacking the immunocompetent

151
00:08:56.824 --> 00:08:58.984
system that human patients have. So to

152
00:09:00.364 --> 00:09:04.184
investigate the role of this variant in a more clinically relevant model, we

153
00:09:04.204 --> 00:09:07.284
decided to create a DAM2 R404W variant

154
00:09:08.224 --> 00:09:09.824
immunocompetent knock-in mouse.

155
00:09:10.444 --> 00:09:13.704
And now that we've generated this mouse, I wanted to ask whether just harboring the

156
00:09:13.744 --> 00:09:17.634
mutation alone could actually elicit any changes in cellular

157
00:09:17.664 --> 00:09:19.654
identity or cellular proliferation.

158
00:09:20.424 --> 00:09:24.024
So I concentrated on the subventricular zone, or SVZ for short.

159
00:09:24.124 --> 00:09:27.744
This is a really highly proliferative area of the brain and the origin of most

160
00:09:27.764 --> 00:09:31.244
brain cells. And so I stained this area with BrdU

161
00:09:31.264 --> 00:09:34.364
proliferation marker as well as cell lineage markers.

162
00:09:34.464 --> 00:09:38.324
And what I noticed was that the R404W mutant

163
00:09:38.384 --> 00:09:42.274
mice had increased number of Sox9-positive, BrdU-positive

164
00:09:42.364 --> 00:09:44.464
cells compared to the wild-type mice.

165
00:09:44.864 --> 00:09:47.714
Now, Sox9 is a marker for glial progenitor cells,

166
00:09:49.044 --> 00:09:52.834
so this suggests that the R404W variant is pushing these cells to a

167
00:09:52.944 --> 00:09:54.324
more glial-like fate.

168
00:09:55.644 --> 00:09:59.204
Interestingly, I did not see any changes in global proliferation,

169
00:09:59.704 --> 00:10:03.604
so I hypothesized that an expansion of glial cells would mean a decrease

170
00:10:03.644 --> 00:10:07.444
in a different type of cell. And sure enough, when I stained for double cortin,

171
00:10:07.544 --> 00:10:11.404
which is a juvenile neuron marker, we can

172
00:10:11.484 --> 00:10:15.244
see a substantial decrease in the double cortin-positive,

173
00:10:15.564 --> 00:10:19.184
BrdU-positive cells in the mutants compared to the wild-type mice.

174
00:10:20.764 --> 00:10:24.104
And so because these mice are a complete whole body knock-in for the

175
00:10:24.144 --> 00:10:27.384
mutation, I was wondering whether or not this change that we see

176
00:10:28.204 --> 00:10:31.984
is a cell intrinsic or extrinsic mechanism.

177
00:10:32.784 --> 00:10:36.684
So to answer that, I decided to isolate neural stem cells from these

178
00:10:37.204 --> 00:10:39.744
wild-type or mutant mice and grow them in culture.

179
00:10:40.134 --> 00:10:43.904
I gave them a pro-astrocytic cue to synchronize their cell fates,

180
00:10:44.364 --> 00:10:44.744
and

181
00:10:46.064 --> 00:10:49.704
that way any kind of differences we see in the two populations would

182
00:10:49.724 --> 00:10:53.304
suggest that maybe it's a cell intrinsic mechanism.

183
00:10:53.744 --> 00:10:57.504
I fixed and stained for the same markers, and we saw

184
00:10:57.544 --> 00:11:00.964
similar results. The mutant showed increased number of

185
00:11:01.024 --> 00:11:04.864
BrdU-positive, Sox9-positive cells as well as a decrease

186
00:11:04.964 --> 00:11:07.664
in the double cortin-positive, BrdU-positive cells.

187
00:11:08.104 --> 00:11:11.844
So together, this kind of highlights that the DAM2 R404W

188
00:11:12.144 --> 00:11:16.004
mutation can confer a more cell intrinsic glial progenitor

189
00:11:16.204 --> 00:11:19.944
state. And now this is really important because it kind of

190
00:11:19.964 --> 00:11:23.924
tips the scales towards a more pro-tumorigenic niche, as it

191
00:11:23.964 --> 00:11:27.484
is widely understood that glial progenitors are often the cell of origin for

192
00:11:27.584 --> 00:11:31.544
glioma. So that leads me to my next question, is what does this

193
00:11:31.604 --> 00:11:35.444
all mean in the glioma context? So as a reminder,

194
00:11:35.564 --> 00:11:39.144
the patient with the 404 mutation has low-grade glioma, and in order

195
00:11:39.184 --> 00:11:42.724
to model that, I decided to use the rCas9-tVA

196
00:11:42.804 --> 00:11:46.664
system, which enables cell type-specific gene delivery to the brain.

197
00:11:47.244 --> 00:11:51.124
So by crossing my 404 mice with Nestin-tVA mice, I'm able

198
00:11:51.184 --> 00:11:51.804
to restrict

199
00:11:54.644 --> 00:11:58.484
viral infection into the Nestin-positive cells, and then by injecting

200
00:11:58.544 --> 00:12:01.764
these chicken fibroblasts that overexpress

201
00:12:01.824 --> 00:12:05.494
PDGF-beta, I should be able to create tumors that

202
00:12:05.544 --> 00:12:09.304
are consistent with low-grade glioma by 100

203
00:12:09.344 --> 00:12:12.694
days.So midway through the progression

204
00:12:13.454 --> 00:12:17.354
of these tumors, I looked at proliferation with OLIG2 as a tumor cell

205
00:12:17.414 --> 00:12:21.254
marker, and you can see a marked increase in proliferating tumor cells in the

206
00:12:21.294 --> 00:12:23.674
form of four mutants compared to the wild-type mice.

207
00:12:24.354 --> 00:12:27.574
And now proliferation is just one aspect of tumor growth.

208
00:12:27.694 --> 00:12:29.774
I wanted to also know whether this mutation

209
00:12:30.714 --> 00:12:34.574
is pushing the progression of these tumors from low

210
00:12:34.634 --> 00:12:38.554
grade to high grade. So by using these WHO tumor

211
00:12:38.614 --> 00:12:42.534
grade two and three as a kind of representative image for comparison,

212
00:12:43.254 --> 00:12:46.914
we can see that the mutant tumors, when

213
00:12:46.954 --> 00:12:48.604
compared to those, have

214
00:12:49.734 --> 00:12:53.674
evidence of hypercellularity as well as nuclear atypia, which are

215
00:12:53.694 --> 00:12:57.594
histological hallmarks of perhaps malignant

216
00:12:57.634 --> 00:13:00.814
transformation. And then my most exciting piece of data,

217
00:13:01.994 --> 00:13:05.614
it's still in the preliminary stages, but it seems that the

218
00:13:05.654 --> 00:13:09.534
survival curve that I have going on shows that the R414W

219
00:13:09.634 --> 00:13:13.134
variant can decrease overall survival in the context

220
00:13:13.714 --> 00:13:14.654
of low-grade glioma.

221
00:13:15.573 --> 00:13:19.414
So, currently I'm working on the mechanism, and I did bulk

222
00:13:19.514 --> 00:13:23.324
RNA sequencing on these tumors. And with

223
00:13:23.354 --> 00:13:26.854
doing gene ontology analysis, looking at all the upregulated

224
00:13:27.194 --> 00:13:31.034
genes here, I found a variety of key biological pathways that are

225
00:13:31.094 --> 00:13:34.974
usually evidenced in being pro-tumorigenic.

226
00:13:35.274 --> 00:13:39.214
So just for example, interferon-mediated signaling as well as

227
00:13:39.654 --> 00:13:43.234
cell cycle regulation. So hopefully in the near future, I'm able to

228
00:13:43.274 --> 00:13:46.854
identify some candidate genes or pathways underlying

229
00:13:46.914 --> 00:13:48.254
this project.

230
00:13:49.214 --> 00:13:53.154
So in conclusion, I hope to have convinced some of you that the

231
00:13:53.274 --> 00:13:57.114
R414W mutation in DAM2 can expand the glial

232
00:13:57.134 --> 00:14:00.354
progenitor pool in vitro and in vivo, as well as

233
00:14:00.814 --> 00:14:04.374
increase the tumor growth across many different glioma

234
00:14:04.414 --> 00:14:06.554
models. And with the

235
00:14:08.454 --> 00:14:12.144
conclusion of my thesis work, I'm hoping to be able to identify

236
00:14:12.234 --> 00:14:15.924
or define and characterize the 414 mutation as a hereditary

237
00:14:15.994 --> 00:14:18.164
variant that drives glioma susceptibility.

238
00:14:19.714 --> 00:14:23.574
So with that, I would like to thank my lab, especially my advisor and

239
00:14:23.614 --> 00:14:27.594
my bench mentor. And a special thanks to my collaborators as

240
00:14:27.654 --> 00:14:29.654
well, Dr. Melissa Bondy at Stanford.

241
00:14:30.284 --> 00:14:34.114
She helped identify these genes and has been very crucial in the

242
00:14:34.154 --> 00:14:36.134
success of this work, as well as Dr.

243
00:14:36.234 --> 00:14:40.164
Rao for providing the reagents available for the low-grade

244
00:14:40.214 --> 00:14:40.954
glioma models.

245
00:14:41.834 --> 00:14:44.854
Thank you all for listening, and I'll be happy to take any questions.

